{"title_page": "Digital dark age", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\nThe '''digital dark age''' is a lack of historical information in the digital age as a direct result of outdated file formats, software, or hardware that becomes corrupt, scarce, or inaccessible as technologies evolve and data decay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apps.sciencefriday.com/data/reawakening.html|title=Data Reawakening|work=Science Friday|access-date=2018-03-01|language=en}}</ref>  Future generations may find it difficult or impossible to retrieve [[Electronic document|electronic documents]] and [[multimedia]], because they have been recorded in an [[Obsolescence|obsolete]] and obscure [[file format]], or on an obsolete physical medium, for example, [[floppy disk]]s. The name derives from the term [[Dark Ages (historiography)|''Dark Ages'']] in the sense that there could be a relative lack of records in the digital age, as documents are transferred to digital formats and original copies are lost. An early mention of the term was at a conference of the [[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]] (IFLA) in 1997.<ref name=\"Kuny, 1997\"/> The term was also mentioned in 1998 at the Time and Bits conference,<ref name=\"MacLean, 1999\"/><ref name=\"Brand, 1999\"/> which was co-sponsored by the [[Long Now Foundation]] and the [[Getty Conservation Institute]].\n\n== Proprietary and obsolete file formats ==\nThe problem is not limited to text documents, but applies equally to photos, video, audio and other kinds of electronic documents. One concern leading to the use of the term is that documents are stored on physical [[Digital media|media]] which require special [[Computer hardware|hardware]] in order to be read and that this hardware will not be available in a few decades from the time the document was created. For example, it is already the case that disk drives capable of reading 5\u00bc-inch [[Floppy disk|floppy disks]] are not readily available.\n\nThe digital dark age also applies to the problems which arise due to [[Digital preservation#Migration|obsolete file formats]]. In such a case, it is the lack of necessary [[software]] which causes problems when retrieving stored documents. This is especially problematic when [[Proprietary format|proprietary formats]] are used, in which case it might be impossible to write appropriate software to read the file.\n\n== Magnetic tape data storage ==\n[[Magnetic tape data storage|Magnetic tape data]] storage is a method of storing data on [[magnetic tape]]. It is used as a backup method of storage for [[Digital Storage|digital storage]] and is one way of mitigating a possible digital dark age. For example, in 2011 hundreds of thousands of Google accounts were reset and the data in those accounts went missing. Google was able to restore the data to the email accounts from the data stored on magnetic tape.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/304135|title=Thousands of Gmail users find emails missing|date=2011-02-28|access-date=2018-02-28}}</ref>  Magnetic data storage is also used by financial institutions, hospitals, movie studios, and manufacturing companies to backup content.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apps.sciencefriday.com/data/ghosts.html|title=Ghosts In The Reels|work=Science Friday|access-date=2018-02-28|language=en}}</ref> Magnetic tape can hold hundreds of terabytes of data.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-01-01/scientists-warn-we-may-be-creating-digital-dark-age|title=Scientists warn we may be creating a 'digital dark age'|work=Public Radio International|access-date=2018-03-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Archiving the internet ==\nThe [[Internet Archive]] has stated that one of their goals is to prevent the digital dark age.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/about/|title=About the Internet Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002231304/https://archive.org/about/|archivedate=2 October 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=5 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\nEven [[Vinton Cerf]], Vice President of Google, showed his concerns about data preservation in the annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 2015: \"As the way that we store information about ourselves develops, memories stored in files that use older technology are becoming harder to access. That could mean that historians of the future are unable to learn about our lives\". His suggested solution consists of preserving a sample of every piece of software and hardware that has ever existed so that it never becomes obsolete. He proposed taking an X-ray snapshot of the content, the application and the operating system along with a description of the machine. This information should be then stored, instead of in a museum, in servers in the cloud. <ref>Pallab, Ghosh. 2015. [https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-31450389 \"Google's Vint Cerf warns of 'digital Dark Age'\"]. BBC News, Science & Environment.</ref>\n\n==Historical examples ==\nA famous example is [[NASA]], whose early space records have suffered from a dark age issue more than once. For over a decade, magnetic tapes from the 1976 [[Viking program|Viking]] [[Mars landing]] were unprocessed. When later analyzed, the data was unreadable as it was in an unknown format and the original programmers had either died or left NASA. The images were eventually extracted following many months of puzzling through the data and examining how the recording machines functioned.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/science/lost-on-earth-wealth-of-data-found-in-space.html\n |title      = Lost on Earth: Wealth of Data Found in Space\n |publisher  = New York Times\n |first      = Sandra\n |last       = Blakeslee\n |date       = 20 March 1990\n |accessdate = 7 July 2013\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121109203504/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/science/lost-on-earth-wealth-of-data-found-in-space.html\n |archivedate= 9 November 2012\n|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAnother example is the [[BBC Domesday Project]] in which a survey of the nation was compiled 900 years after the [[Domesday Book]] was published. While the original Domesday Book of 1086 is still readable today, there were great fears that the discs of the 1986 Domesday Project would become unreadable as software and disk drives capable of reading the format became rarer and rarer. However, in 2002 the [[CAMiLEON]] project [[PC migration|migrated]] the information to a system called DomesEm, allowing it to be accessed on modern computers.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/mar/03/research.elearning\n |title      = Digital Domesday Book lasts 15 years not 1000\n |publisher  = The Observer\n |first1     = Robin\n |last1      = McKie\n |first2     = Vanessa\n |last2      = Thorpe\n |date       = 3 March 2002\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130120125028/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2002/mar/03/research.elearning\n |archivedate= 20 January 2013\n|url-status = live}}</ref> More recently, the [https://www.domesday86.com/?page_id=74 Domesday86 Project] has continued this preservation effort by developing a digitizer for the original [[LaserDisc|LaserDiscs]] and emulation software for the original BBC Domesday computer system.\n\n== Encryption and data preservation ==\n[[Encryption]] may exacerbate the problem of preserving data, since decoding adds complexity even when the relevant software is available.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.dpconline.org/advice/preservationhandbook/media-and-formats/compression-and-encryption\n |title       = Media and Formats - Compression and Encryption\n |author      = Digital Preservation Coalition\n |authorlink  = Digital Preservation Coalition\n |year        = 2012\n |work        = Digital Preservation Handbook\n |accessdate  = 17 August 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120729192407/http://dpconline.org/advice/preservationhandbook/media-and-formats/compression-and-encryption\n |archivedate = 29 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> Historically, encrypted data is quite rare, but even the very simple means available throughout history have provided many examples of documents that can only be read with great effort. For example, it took the capacity of a distributed computing project to break the mechanically generated code of a single brief [[World War II]] [[submarine]] tactical message.<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://news.cnet.com/2100-1029_3-6043572.html?part=rss\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/5v6Esfshc?url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1029_3-6043572.html?part=rss\n |archivedate = 19 December 2010\n |title       = Distributed computing cracks Enigma code\n |publisher   = CNET News\n |first       = Graeme\n |last        = Wearden\n |date        = 27 February 2006\n |url-status     = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Modern encryption is being used in many more documents and media due to publishers wanting the promised protections of [[Digital rights management|DRM]].\n\n==Open source file formats==\nAs more records are stored in digital form, there have been several measures to standardize electronic file formats so software to read them is widely available and can be re-implemented on new platforms if necessary.\n\n[[PDF/A]] is an [[open standard]] based on [[Adobe Systems]] [[PDF]] format.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://acroeng.adobe.com/wp/?page_id=303|title = Adobe Acrobat Engineering:PDF Standards|accessdate = 7 July 2013|date = 12 March 2013|publisher = Adobe|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130707172612/http://acroeng.adobe.com/wp/?page_id=303|archivedate = 7 July 2013|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref> It has been widely adopted by governments and archives around the world, such as the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Viewing government documents|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/open-standards-for-government/viewing-government-documents|publisher=Cabinet Office|website=GOV.UK|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[OpenDocument|The Open Document Format for Office Applications (OpenDocument)]] has been standardized by [[OASIS (organization)|OASIS]] in 2005, and by ISO in 2006. Since then, support for OpenDocument has been implemented in [[OpenDocument software|a large number of open source and proprietary software]]. Therefore, using OpenDocument is one option for archiving editable documents from office applications. More broadly, the use of [[open source software]] is a prevention measure.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cassia |first=Fernando |title=Open Source, the only weapon against 'planned obsolescence' |date=March 28, 2007 |publisher=[[The Inquirer]] |url=http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1001739/open-source-weapon-planned-obsolescence |accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> Since the [[source code]] for reading and writing a file format is open, the code can be used as a base for future implementations. In 2007, the chief information officer of the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|UK's National Archives]] stated \"We welcome open-source software because it makes our lives easier\".<ref>{{cite web \n |url        = http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/it-strategy/2007/07/19/defending-against-the-digital-dark-age-39288099/\n |title      = Defending against the digital dark age\n |publisher  = ZDNet\n |first      = Andrew\n |last       = Donoghue\n |date       = 19 July 2007\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121023075347/http://www.zdnet.com/defending-against-the-digital-dark-age-3039288099/\n |archivedate= 23 October 2012\n |url-status    = live}}</ref>\n\n== Data storage standardization ==\nIn 2007, [[Microsoft]] created a partnership with the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|UK's National Archives]] to prevent the digital dark age and \"unlock millions of unreadable stored computer files\".<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2007/jul/04/news.uknews\n |title      = National Archive project to avert digital dark age\n |last       = Kennedy\n |first      = Maev\n |date       = 4 July 2007\n |work       = News:Technology\n |publisher  = The Guardian\n |accessdate = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100717121702/http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2007/jul/04/news.uknews\n |archivedate= 17 July 2010\n|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2007/gb2007075_877434.htm\n |title       = Microsoft Helps Archives Save the Past\n |last        = Ferguson\n |first       = Tim\n |date        = 5 July 2007\n |work        = Technology\n |publisher   = Business Week\n |accessdate  = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070710062846/http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2007/gb2007075_877434.htm\n |archivedate = 10 July 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/3353826/How-to-stave-off-a-digital-dark-age.html\n |title      = How to stave off a digital 'dark age'\n |last       = Colvile\n |first      = Robert\n |date       = 5 July 2007\n |publisher  = Telegraph\n |accessdate = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120424121440/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/3353826/How-to-stave-off-a-digital-dark-age.html\n |archivedate= 24 April 2012\n|url-status = live}}</ref> UK's National Archives now accepts various file formats for long term sustenance, including [[Office Open XML]], PDF and OpenDocument.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/information-management/manage-information/selection-and-transfer/digital-records-transfer/file-formats-transfer/|title = File formats for transfer - The National Archives}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThe notion of the digital dark age has been criticized by some scholars. Some of these view it as alarmist rhetoric such as David Anderson and Jon Tilbury who maintained that such \"dark age\" incorrectly states the current condition. They argued that there has been significant progress in digital preservation and evidenced in the way organizations continue to find and reuse critical long-term digital information while finding new ways of sharing these with the public.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Preserving Digital Materials, Third Edition|last=Harvey|first=Ross|last2=Weatherburn|first2=Jaye|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781538102961|location=Lanham, MD|pages=25}}</ref> Some historians also fault proponents of the digital dark age for historical inaccuracies. These include Marilyn Deegan and Simon Tanner's claim that the [[Johannes Gutenberg|Gutenberg]] [[printing]] revolution led Europe out of the Dark Ages, a period said to be marked by the loss of knowledge of the learning of the [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]] and [[Ancient Rome|Romans]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=History in the Digital Age|last=Weller|first=Toni|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=9780415666961|location=Oxon|pages=58}}</ref> It is argued that knowledge and information about classical learning had been recovered during the Middle Ages and it was not mainly due to the printing revolution but it was largely a result of the intellectual exchange between [[Islam|Islamic]] and [[Christianity|Christian]] cultures.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digital Information Culture: The Individual and Society in the Digital Age|last=Tredinnick|first=Luke|publisher=Chandos Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9781843341703|location=Oxford|pages=155}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apollo 11 missing tapes]]\n* [[Dark data]]\n* [[Data archaeology]]\n* [[Data corruption]]\n* [[Digital continuity]]\n* [[Digital obsolescence]]\n* [[Digital preservation]]\n* [[Orphan work|Orphaned works]]\n* [[Abandonware]]\n* [[M-DISC]]\n* [[Document Freedom Day]]\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"Kuny, 1997\">{{cite journal\n  |title = A Digital Dark Ages? Challenges in the Preservation of Electronic Prevention Information\n  |first = Terry\n  |last = Kuny\n  |journal = 63RD IFLA ([[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]]) Council and General Conference\n  |date = September 1997\n  |url = http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf\n  |format = PDF\n  |accessdate = 7 November 2011\n  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080509145855/http://www.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf\n |archivedate = 9 May 2008\n |url-status = live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MacLean, 1999\">{{cite book\n |first = Margaret\n |last = MacLean\n |editors = MacLean, Margaret & Davis, Ben\n |title = Time and Bits, Managing Digital Continuity\n |publisher = [[Getty Research Institute|Getty]]\n |year = 1999\n |isbn = 978-0-89236-583-8}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Brand, 1999\">{{cite journal\n |title = Escaping The Digital Dark Age\n |last = Brand\n |first = Steven\n |authorlink = Steven Brand\n |journal = Library Journal\n |volume = 124\n |issue = 2\n |pages = 46\u201369\n |date = 1 February 1999\n |issn = 0363-0277\n |url = http://library.colstate.edu/libr1105/kramer/cadeau/deadm2.html\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050923024519/http://library.colstate.edu/libr1105/kramer/cadeau/deadm2.html\n |archivedate = 23 September 2005\n |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf A Digital Dark Ages? Challenges in the Preservation of Electronic Information (PDF)], 1997\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/01/21/tech/main537308.shtml Coming Soon A Digital Dark Age - CBS News], 2003\n* [http://technology.guardian.co.uk/online/story/0,3605,871091,00.html How huge quantities of data are rapidly falling into a black hole - Guardian Unlimited], 2003\n* [https://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/the-digital-dark-age/2005/09/22/1126982184206.html The digital Dark Age - The Sydney Morning Herald], 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324044358/http://www.pcworld.in/news/why-demise-print-media-may-be-bad-humanity-65952012 Why the Demise of Print Media May Be Bad for Humanity, Tony Bradley, PCWorld, 19 March 2012]\n* [http://www.economist.com/node/21553445 Bit Rot - The Economist, 28 April 2012]\n* {{citation |work=[[The Atlantic]] |location=USA |title=Raiders of the Lost Web |date=October 2015 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/raiders-of-the-lost-web/409210/ }}\n*[http://www.dejavublog.in/2016/02/what-if-digital-dark-age-is-real.html What If Digital Dark Age Is Real?, Pallav Gogoi, Dejavublog, 2016]\n\n{{ external media\n| float  =\n| width  =\n| video1 = [http://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/memory-storage/8/325/2208 Digital Dark Age] ([[Computer History Museum]], 2011)\n}}\n\n{{DigitalPreservation}}\n\n[[Category:Future]]\n[[Category:Lost works]]\n[[Category:Digital preservation]]\n[[Category:Dark ages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\nThe '''digital dark age''' is a lack of historical information in the digital age as a direct result of outdated file formats, software, or hardware that becomes corrupt, scarce, or inaccessible as technologies evolve and data decay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apps.sciencefriday.com/data/reawakening.html|title=Data Reawakening|work=Science Friday|access-date=2018-03-01|language=en}}</ref>  Future generations may find it difficult or impossible to retrieve [[Electronic document|electronic documents]] and [[multimedia]], because they have been recorded in an [[Obsolescence|obsolete]] and obscure [[file format]], or on an obsolete physical medium, for example, [[floppy disk]]s. The name derives from the term [[Dark Ages (historiography)|''Dark Ages'']] in the sense that there could be a relative lack of records in the digital age, as documents are transferred to digital formats and original copies are lost. An early mention of the term was at a conference of the [[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]] (IFLA) in 1997.<ref name=\"Kuny, 1997\"/> The term was also mentioned in 1998 at the Time and Bits conference,<ref name=\"MacLean, 1999\"/><ref name=\"Brand, 1999\"/> which was co-sponsored by the [[Long Now Foundation]] and the [[Getty Conservation Institute]].\n\n== Proprietary and obsolete file formats ==\nThe problem is not limited to text documents, but applies equally to photos, video, audio and other kinds of electronic documents. One concern leading to the use of the term is that documents are stored on physical [[Digital media|media]] which require special [[Computer hardware|hardware]] in order to be read and that this hardware will not be available in a few decades from the time the document was created. For example, it is already the case that disk drives capable of reading 5\u00bc-inch [[Floppy disk|floppy disks]] are not readily available.\n\nThe digital dark age also applies to the problems which arise due to [[Digital preservation#Migration|obsolete file formats]]. In such a case, it is the lack of necessary [[software]] which causes problems when retrieving stored documents. This is especially problematic when [[Proprietary format|proprietary formats]] are used, in which case it might be impossible to write appropriate software to read the file.\n\n== Magnetic tape data storage ==\n[[Magnetic tape data storage|Magnetic tape data]] storage is a method of storing data on [[magnetic tape]]. It is used as a backup method of storage for [[Digital Storage|digital storage]] and is one way of mitigating a possible digital dark age. For example, in 2011 hundreds of thousands of Google accounts were reset and the data in those accounts went missing. Google was able to restore the data to the email accounts from the data stored on magnetic tape.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/304135|title=Thousands of Gmail users find emails missing|date=2011-02-28|access-date=2018-02-28}}</ref>  Magnetic data storage is also used by financial institutions, hospitals, movie studios, and manufacturing companies to backup content.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apps.sciencefriday.com/data/ghosts.html|title=Ghosts In The Reels|work=Science Friday|access-date=2018-02-28|language=en}}</ref> Magnetic tape can hold hundreds of terabytes of data.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-01-01/scientists-warn-we-may-be-creating-digital-dark-age|title=Scientists warn we may be creating a 'digital dark age'|work=Public Radio International|access-date=2018-03-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Archiving the internet ==\nThe [[Internet Archive]] has stated that one of their goals is to prevent the digital dark age.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/about/|title=About the Internet Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002231304/https://archive.org/about/|archivedate=2 October 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=5 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\nEven [[Vinton Cerf]], Vice President of Google, showed his concerns about data preservation in the annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science: \"As the way that we store information about ourselves develops, memories stored in files that use older technology are becoming harder to access. That could mean that historians of the future are unable to learn about our lives\". His suggested solution consists of preserving a sample of every piece of software and hardware that has ever existed so that it never becomes obsolete. He proposed taking an X-ray snapshot of the content, the application and the operating system along with a description of the machine. This information should be then stored, instead of in a museum, in servers in the cloud. <ref>Pallab, Ghosh. 2015. [https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-31450389 \"Google's Vint Cerf warns of 'digital Dark Age'\"]. BBC News, Science & Environment.</ref>\n\n==Historical examples ==\nA famous example is [[NASA]], whose early space records have suffered from a dark age issue more than once. For over a decade, magnetic tapes from the 1976 [[Viking program|Viking]] [[Mars landing]] were unprocessed. When later analyzed, the data was unreadable as it was in an unknown format and the original programmers had either died or left NASA. The images were eventually extracted following many months of puzzling through the data and examining how the recording machines functioned.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/science/lost-on-earth-wealth-of-data-found-in-space.html\n |title      = Lost on Earth: Wealth of Data Found in Space\n |publisher  = New York Times\n |first      = Sandra\n |last       = Blakeslee\n |date       = 20 March 1990\n |accessdate = 7 July 2013\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121109203504/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/science/lost-on-earth-wealth-of-data-found-in-space.html\n |archivedate= 9 November 2012\n|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAnother example is the [[BBC Domesday Project]] in which a survey of the nation was compiled 900 years after the [[Domesday Book]] was published. While the original Domesday Book is still readable today, there were great fears that the discs of the Domesday Project would become unreadable as software and disk drives capable of reading the format became rarer and rarer. However, in 2002 the [[CAMiLEON]] project [[PC migration|migrated]] the information to a system called DomesEm, allowing it to be accessed on modern computers.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/mar/03/research.elearning\n |title      = Digital Domesday Book lasts 15 years not 1000\n |publisher  = The Observer\n |first1     = Robin\n |last1      = McKie\n |first2     = Vanessa\n |last2      = Thorpe\n |date       = 3 March 2002\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130120125028/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2002/mar/03/research.elearning\n |archivedate= 20 January 2013\n|url-status = live}}</ref> More recently, the [https://www.domesday86.com/?page_id=74 Domesday86 Project] has continued this preservation effort by developing a digitizer for the original [[LaserDisc|LaserDiscs]] and emulation software for the original BBC Domesday computer system.\n\n== Encryption and data preservation ==\n[[Encryption]] may exacerbate the problem of preserving data, since decoding adds complexity even when the relevant software is available.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.dpconline.org/advice/preservationhandbook/media-and-formats/compression-and-encryption\n |title       = Media and Formats - Compression and Encryption\n |author      = Digital Preservation Coalition\n |authorlink  = Digital Preservation Coalition\n |year        = 2012\n |work        = Digital Preservation Handbook\n |accessdate  = 17 August 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120729192407/http://dpconline.org/advice/preservationhandbook/media-and-formats/compression-and-encryption\n |archivedate = 29 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> Historically, encrypted data is quite rare, but even the very simple means available throughout history have provided many examples of documents that can only be read with great effort. For example, it took the capacity of a distributed computing project to break the mechanically generated code of a single brief [[World War II]] [[submarine]] tactical message.<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://news.cnet.com/2100-1029_3-6043572.html?part=rss\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/5v6Esfshc?url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1029_3-6043572.html?part=rss\n |archivedate = 19 December 2010\n |title       = Distributed computing cracks Enigma code\n |publisher   = CNET News\n |first       = Graeme\n |last        = Wearden\n |date        = 27 February 2006\n |url-status     = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Modern encryption is being used in many more documents and media due to publishers wanting the promised protections of [[Digital rights management|DRM]].\n\n==Open source file formats==\nAs more records are stored in digital form, there have been several measures to standardize electronic file formats so software to read them is widely available and can be re-implemented on new platforms if necessary.\n\n[[PDF/A]] is an [[open standard]] based on [[Adobe Systems]] [[PDF]] format.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://acroeng.adobe.com/wp/?page_id=303|title = Adobe Acrobat Engineering:PDF Standards|accessdate = 7 July 2013|date = 12 March 2013|publisher = Adobe|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130707172612/http://acroeng.adobe.com/wp/?page_id=303|archivedate = 7 July 2013|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref> It has been widely adopted by governments and archives around the world, such as the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Viewing government documents|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/open-standards-for-government/viewing-government-documents|publisher=Cabinet Office|website=GOV.UK|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[OpenDocument|The Open Document Format for Office Applications (OpenDocument)]] has been standardized by [[OASIS (organization)|OASIS]] in 2005, and by ISO in 2006. Since then, support for OpenDocument has been implemented in [[OpenDocument software|a large number of open source and proprietary software]]. Therefore, using OpenDocument is one option for archiving editable documents from office applications. More broadly, the use of [[open source software]] is a prevention measure.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cassia |first=Fernando |title=Open Source, the only weapon against 'planned obsolescence' |date=March 28, 2007 |publisher=[[The Inquirer]] |url=http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1001739/open-source-weapon-planned-obsolescence |accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> Since the [[source code]] for reading and writing a file format is open, the code can be used as a base for future implementations. In 2007, the chief information officer of the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|UK's National Archives]] stated \"We welcome open-source software because it makes our lives easier\".<ref>{{cite web \n |url        = http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/it-strategy/2007/07/19/defending-against-the-digital-dark-age-39288099/\n |title      = Defending against the digital dark age\n |publisher  = ZDNet\n |first      = Andrew\n |last       = Donoghue\n |date       = 19 July 2007\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121023075347/http://www.zdnet.com/defending-against-the-digital-dark-age-3039288099/\n |archivedate= 23 October 2012\n |url-status    = live}}</ref>\n\n== Data storage standardization ==\nIn 2007, [[Microsoft]] created a partnership with the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|UK's National Archives]] to prevent the digital dark age and \"unlock millions of unreadable stored computer files\".<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2007/jul/04/news.uknews\n |title      = National Archive project to avert digital dark age\n |last       = Kennedy\n |first      = Maev\n |date       = 4 July 2007\n |work       = News:Technology\n |publisher  = The Guardian\n |accessdate = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100717121702/http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2007/jul/04/news.uknews\n |archivedate= 17 July 2010\n|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2007/gb2007075_877434.htm\n |title       = Microsoft Helps Archives Save the Past\n |last        = Ferguson\n |first       = Tim\n |date        = 5 July 2007\n |work        = Technology\n |publisher   = Business Week\n |accessdate  = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070710062846/http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2007/gb2007075_877434.htm\n |archivedate = 10 July 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url        = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/3353826/How-to-stave-off-a-digital-dark-age.html\n |title      = How to stave off a digital 'dark age'\n |last       = Colvile\n |first      = Robert\n |date       = 5 July 2007\n |publisher  = Telegraph\n |accessdate = 7 October 2009\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120424121440/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/3353826/How-to-stave-off-a-digital-dark-age.html\n |archivedate= 24 April 2012\n|url-status = live}}</ref> UK's National Archives now accepts various file formats for long term sustenance, including [[Office Open XML]], PDF and OpenDocument.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/information-management/manage-information/selection-and-transfer/digital-records-transfer/file-formats-transfer/|title = File formats for transfer - The National Archives}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThe notion of the digital dark age has been criticized by some scholars. Some of these view it as alarmist rhetoric such as David Anderson and Jon Tilbury who maintained that such \"dark age\" incorrectly states the current condition. They argued that there has been significant progress in digital preservation and evidenced in the way organizations continue to find and reuse critical long-term digital information while finding new ways of sharing these with the public.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Preserving Digital Materials, Third Edition|last=Harvey|first=Ross|last2=Weatherburn|first2=Jaye|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781538102961|location=Lanham, MD|pages=25}}</ref> Some historians also fault proponents of the digital dark age for historical inaccuracies. These include Marilyn Deegan and Simon Tanner's claim that the [[Johannes Gutenberg|Gutenberg]] [[printing]] revolution led Europe out of the Dark Ages, a period said to be marked by the loss of knowledge of the learning of the [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]] and [[Ancient Rome|Romans]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=History in the Digital Age|last=Weller|first=Toni|publisher=Routledge|year=2013|isbn=9780415666961|location=Oxon|pages=58}}</ref> It is argued that knowledge and information about classical learning had been recovered during the Middle Ages and it was not mainly due to the printing revolution but it was largely a result of the intellectual exchange between [[Islam|Islamic]] and [[Christianity|Christian]] cultures.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digital Information Culture: The Individual and Society in the Digital Age|last=Tredinnick|first=Luke|publisher=Chandos Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9781843341703|location=Oxford|pages=155}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apollo 11 missing tapes]]\n* [[Dark data]]\n* [[Data archaeology]]\n* [[Data corruption]]\n* [[Digital continuity]]\n* [[Digital obsolescence]]\n* [[Digital preservation]]\n* [[Orphan work|Orphaned works]]\n* [[Abandonware]]\n* [[M-DISC]]\n* [[Document Freedom Day]]\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"Kuny, 1997\">{{cite journal\n  |title = A Digital Dark Ages? Challenges in the Preservation of Electronic Prevention Information\n  |first = Terry\n  |last = Kuny\n  |journal = 63RD IFLA ([[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]]) Council and General Conference\n  |date = September 1997\n  |url = http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf\n  |format = PDF\n  |accessdate = 7 November 2011\n  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080509145855/http://www.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf\n |archivedate = 9 May 2008\n |url-status = live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MacLean, 1999\">{{cite book\n |first = Margaret\n |last = MacLean\n |editors = MacLean, Margaret & Davis, Ben\n |title = Time and Bits, Managing Digital Continuity\n |publisher = [[Getty Research Institute|Getty]]\n |year = 1999\n |isbn = 978-0-89236-583-8}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Brand, 1999\">{{cite journal\n |title = Escaping The Digital Dark Age\n |last = Brand\n |first = Steven\n |authorlink = Steven Brand\n |journal = Library Journal\n |volume = 124\n |issue = 2\n |pages = 46\u201369\n |date = 1 February 1999\n |issn = 0363-0277\n |url = http://library.colstate.edu/libr1105/kramer/cadeau/deadm2.html\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050923024519/http://library.colstate.edu/libr1105/kramer/cadeau/deadm2.html\n |archivedate = 23 September 2005\n |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.ifla.org/IV/ifla63/63kuny1.pdf A Digital Dark Ages? Challenges in the Preservation of Electronic Information (PDF)], 1997\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/01/21/tech/main537308.shtml Coming Soon A Digital Dark Age - CBS News], 2003\n* [http://technology.guardian.co.uk/online/story/0,3605,871091,00.html How huge quantities of data are rapidly falling into a black hole - Guardian Unlimited], 2003\n* [https://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/the-digital-dark-age/2005/09/22/1126982184206.html The digital Dark Age - The Sydney Morning Herald], 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324044358/http://www.pcworld.in/news/why-demise-print-media-may-be-bad-humanity-65952012 Why the Demise of Print Media May Be Bad for Humanity, Tony Bradley, PCWorld, 19 March 2012]\n* [http://www.economist.com/node/21553445 Bit Rot - The Economist, 28 April 2012]\n* {{citation |work=[[The Atlantic]] |location=USA |title=Raiders of the Lost Web |date=October 2015 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/raiders-of-the-lost-web/409210/ }}\n*[http://www.dejavublog.in/2016/02/what-if-digital-dark-age-is-real.html What If Digital Dark Age Is Real?, Pallav Gogoi, Dejavublog, 2016]\n\n{{ external media\n| float  =\n| width  =\n| video1 = [http://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/memory-storage/8/325/2208 Digital Dark Age] ([[Computer History Museum]], 2011)\n}}\n\n{{DigitalPreservation}}\n\n[[Category:Future]]\n[[Category:Lost works]]\n[[Category:Digital preservation]]\n[[Category:Dark ages]]\n", "name_user": "Coldspur", "label": "safe", "comment": "improved clarity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_dark_age"}
{"title_page": "%TMP%", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Environment variable#%TMP%]]\n\n{{Redirect category shell|1=\n{{R to anchor}}\n}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Environment variable#%TMP%]]\n\n{{Redirect category shell|1=\n{{R to anchor}}\n{{R from modification}}\n}}\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:remove rcat, seeTalk:%APPEND%#Rcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%25TMP%25&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development\n| native_name  = \n| logo         =\n| logo_caption =\n| image        = <!--DO NOT include \"File:\" part of image name\n                 (different from above because of merger with\n                 Template:Infobox festival)-->Rio+20_logo.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = \n| date         = 13\u201322 June 2012<ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\"/><ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/>\n| prev         = [[Earth Summit|Earth Summit 1992]]<br />[[Earth Summit 2002]]\n| next         = \n| frequency    =\n| location     = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| years_active =\n| first        = <!--\"founded=\" also works-->\n| participants =\n| attendance   =\n| genre        =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organized=\" also works-->\n| website      = [https://web.archive.org/web/20110420002837/http://www.uncsd2012.org/ uncsd2012]\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n\nThe '''United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development''' ('''UNCSD'''), also known as '''Rio 2012''', '''Rio+20''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8\u0281i.u \u02c8maj\u0292 \u02c8v\u0129t\u0283i}}), or '''Earth Summit 2012''' was the third international conference on [[sustainable development]] aimed at reconciling the economic and environmental goals of the global community. Hosted by [[Brazil]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] from 13 to 22 June 2012,<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/><ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\"/> Rio+20 was a 20-year follow-up to the 1992 [[Earth Summit|United Nations Conference on Environment and Development]] (UNCED) held in the same city, and the 10th anniversary of the 2002 [[Earth Summit 2002|World Summit on Sustainable Development]] (WSSD) in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nThe ten-day mega-summit, which culminated in a three-day high-level UN conference, was organized by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs and included participation from 192 UN member states \u2013 including 57 Heads of State and 31 Heads of Government, private sector companies, NGOs and other groups. The decision to hold the conference was made by UN General Assembly Resolution A/RES/64/236 on 24 December 2009. It was intended to be a high-level conference, including heads of state and government or other representatives and resulting in a focused political document designed to shape global environmental policy.<ref name=\"about.html\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/about.html |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=22 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140818215812/http://www.uncsd2012.org/about.html |archivedate=18 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the final three days of the Conference, from 20 to 22 June 2012, world leaders and representatives met for intense meetings which culminated in finalizing the non-binding document, \"The World We Want\" which opens with \"We the Heads of State and Government and high-level representatives\", having met at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 20 to 22 June 2012, with the full participation of civil society, renew our commitment to sustainable development and to ensuring the promotion of an economically, socially and environmentally sustainable future for our planet and for present and future generations.\"<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nIn 1992, the first conference of its kind, the [[United Nations Conference on Environment and Development]] ([[UNCED]]), commonly referred to as the Rio Conference or Earth Summit, succeeded in raising public awareness of the need to integrate environment and development. The conference drew 109 heads of state to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], to address what were dubbed urgent problems of environmental protection and socio-economic development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/esa/earthsummit/ |title=United Nations Earth Summit+5 |publisher=United Nations |date=27 June 1997 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The Earth Summit influenced subsequent UN conferences, including Rio+20 and set the global green agenda. \"The World Conference on Human Rights, for example, focused on the right of people to a healthy environment and the right to development; controversial demands that had met with resistance from some Member States until the Earth Summit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/geninfo/bp/enviro.html/ |title=Earth_Summit |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nMajor outcomes of the conference include the [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC) \u2014a climate-change agreement that led to the [[Kyoto Protocol]], [[Agenda 21]], the [[United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity]] (CBD) and the [[United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification]] (UNCCD). It also created new international institutions, among them the Commission on Sustainable Development, tasked with the follow-up to the Rio Conference and led to the reform of the [[Global Environment Facility]].<ref name=\"isfd.html\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/isfd.html |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=29 July 2011 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nTen years later, [[Earth Summit 2002]] informally nicknamed Rio+10 was held in Johannesburg, South Africa with the goal of again bringing together leaders from government, business and NGOs to agree on a range of measures toward similar goals. At Rio+10, [[sustainable development]] was recognized as an overarching goal for institutions at the national, regional and international levels. There, the need to enhance the integration of sustainable development in the activities of all relevant United Nations agencies, programs and funds was highlighted. The discussion also encompassed the role of institutions in stepping up efforts to bridge the gap between the international financial institutions and the multilateral development banks and the rest of the UN system.<ref name=\"isfd.html\"/>\n\nMajor outcomes of that conference include the [[Johannesburg Declaration]] and almost 300 international partnership initiatives meant to help achieve the [[Millennium Development Goals]].\n\n== Objectives ==\n\nThe conference had three objectives\u2014to secure renewed political commitment for sustainable development, to assess the progress and implementation gaps in meeting previous commitments, and to address new and emerging challenges.\n\n== Conference themes ==\nThe official discussions had two main themes, how to build a [[green economy]] to achieve sustainable development and lift people out of poverty, including support for developing countries that will allow them to find a green path for development; and how to improve international coordination for sustainable development by building an institutional framework.\n\n== Rio+20 formal preparatory process ==\n\nIn the months leading up to the beginning of the conference, negotiators held frequent informal consultations at UN headquarters in [[New York City]], and in the two weeks before the conference was scheduled to begin, they managed to reach consensus on the sensitive language in the then proposed outcome document for the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/136199/ |title=Agreement Reached on Weakened Outcome Text as Leaders Arrive for Rio Summit &#124; International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development |publisher=Ictsd.org |date=31 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to historian [[Felix Dodds]] in his 2014 co-authored 2014 book entitled, ''From Rio+20 to a New Development Agenda: Building a Bridge to a Sustainable Future'', the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development\u2014Rio+20 formal preparatory process, can be divided into three phases. \n\nPhase one took place from May 2010 to January 2012\u2014when preliminary intergovernmental discussions and negotiations began, and national, regional, and local level preparations were being made. This stage ended with the January 2012 publication of the draft document, \"The Future We Want\"<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\">{{Cite book| edition = 1| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 978-0-415-71654-3| last1 = Dodds| first1 = Felix| last2 = Laguna-Celis| first2 = Jorges| last3 = Thompson| first3 = Liz| title = From Rio+20 to a New Development Agenda| location = New York| date = 7 February 2014 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=CBSkAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=preparatory+process+Rio%2B20+13+June+to+15+2012&source=bl&ots=lXHjNwHBic&sig=ACfU3U2k9HsNvI0FfSSA-2ne8uGPN3CdeQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFnd29xtnoAhVBj54KHasTDH4Q6AEwAHoECAwQLA#v=onepage&q=13%20June%20to%2015%202012&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/17/world/americas/brazils-president-dilma-rousseff-faces-defining-decision-over-forest-bill.html|title=Brazil's Leader Faces Defining Decision on Bill Relaxing Protection of Forests | work=The New York Times | first=Simon|last=Romero|date=16 May 2012}}</ref> The 1st Preparatory Committee was held from 16\u201318 May 2010, immediately after the conclusion of the eighteenth session and the first meeting of the nineteenth session of the [[Commission on Sustainable Development]]. The 1st Intersessional\u2014which was not a negotiation session \u2013 featured panel discussions, from academia, non-governmental organizations as well as Delegates and UN system representatives\u2014was held from 10\u201311 January 2011 at UN Headquarters, [[New York City|New York]]. The 2nd Preparatory Committee was held from 7\u20138 March 2011, at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York, immediately following the Intergovernmental Policy Meeting for the 19th Session of the [[Commission on Sustainable Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=72&Itemid=123 |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=22 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The 2nd Intersessional was held from 15\u201316 December 2011 at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110728143834/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/index.php?page=view&type=13&nr=42&menu=46 ]</ref>\n\nPhase two\u2014from March 2012 to April 2012\u2014began with the first informal negotiations and concluded with the April 2012 release of co-chairs streamline text of \"The Future We Want\".<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/> The 3rd Intersessional was held from 5\u20137 March 2012 at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111111053059/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/index.php?page=view&type=13&nr=46&menu=46 ]</ref>\n\nPhase three\u2014from April 9, 2012 to June 15, 2012\u2014began with the second round of negotiations starting on April 9, 2012, and ending with the June 15, 2012 closing of the Third Preparatory Committee meeting, when negotiators were already in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/> Th three-day intense meetings with hundreds of \"heads of states from around the world\" met in Rio de Janeiro after the 3rd Preparatory Meeting had concluded.<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/>\n\n==United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development ==\n\nAccording to a 13 June 2012 ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' article, the \"giant, 10-day-long\" Conference underway in Rio de Janeiro which would end on June 22, 2012, was \"expected to draw 50,000 participants, including delegates, environmental activists, business leaders, and indigenous groups.\" For the final three days of the conference, \"about 130 heads of state from around the world were expected to be present.\"<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/giant-10-day-long-un-conference-on-sustainable-development-gets-underway-in-rio-de-janeiro/2012/06/13/gJQAbPGVaV_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614083725/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/giant-10-day-long-un-conference-on-sustainable-development-gets-underway-in-rio-de-janeiro/2012/06/13/gJQAbPGVaV_story.html|archive-date=14 June 2012|title=Giant, 10-day-long UN conference on sustainable development gets underway in Rio de Janeiro|work=[[The Washington Post]] via [[Associated Press]]|date=13 June 2012|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\">{{Cite journal| journal = Earth Negotiations Bulletin |volume=27 |number=51 |publisher=[[International Institute for Sustainable Development]] (IISD) |date=25 June 2012|series=A Reporting Service for Environment and Development Negotiations (UNCSD) |title=Summary of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development: 13-22 June 2012| access-date = 8 April 2020| url = https://enb.iisd.org/download/pdf/enb2751e.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBilled as the biggest UN event ever organized\u2014with 15,000 soldiers and police guarding about 130 heads of state and government, from 192 countries, and the more than 45,000 individuals gathered in [[Rio de Janeiro]]\u2014the 10-day mega-conference was intended to be a high-level international gathering organized to re-direct and renew global political commitment to the three dimensions of sustainable development: economic growth, social improvement and environmental protection; focusing on reducing poverty while promoting  jobs growth, clean energy and more fair, sustainable uses of resources; goals first established at Earth Summit in 1992.<ref name=\"about.html\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/newsletter.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=4 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825072833/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/newsletter.html |archivedate=25 August 2012 }}</ref> \n<ref>[http://www.environment.gov.au/rio/index.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724110850/http://www.environment.gov.au/rio/index.html |date=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe conference centered around Agenda 21, the outcome document from Earth Summit 1992. That document was considered revolutionary in that it essentially created the term sustainable development and created the global environmental agenda for the next 20 years. The representatives of participating governments gathered in Rio to discuss what was then the draft text of the outcome document.\n\nRio+20 sought to secure affirmations for the political commitments made at past Earth Summits and set the global environmental agenda for the next 20 years by assessing progress towards the goals set forth in Agenda 21 and implementation gaps therein, and discussing new and emerging issues.\n<ref name=\"Gerhardt\">{{Cite news|last=Gerhardt|first=Tina|date=20 June 2012|title=Rio+20 Kicks Off|url=http://www.progressive.org/rio_20_kicks_off.html|work=[[The Progressive]]}}</ref> The UN wanted Rio to endorse a UN \"green economy roadmap\", with environmental goals, targets and deadlines, whereas developing countries preferred establishing new \"sustainable development goals\" to better protect the environment, guarantee food and power to the poorest, and alleviate poverty.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/19/rio-20-earth-summit-1992-2012 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=John | last=Vidal | title=Rio+20: Earth summit dawns with stormier clouds than in 1992 | date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRio+20 attracted many protests, and more than 500 parallel events, exhibitions, presentations, fairs and announcements as a wide range of diverse groups struggled to take advantage of the conference in order to gain international attention. The British online newspaper, The Guardian reported that, \"Downtown Rio de Janeiro was partly shut-down as an estimated 50,000 protesters, some of whom were naked, took to the streets.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2012/jun/21/rio20-summit-opens-protests-video | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Rio+20 summit opens amid protests \u2013 video | date=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== The future we want ===\nFrom 20 to 22 June 2012, world leaders and representatives met for intense meetings which culminated in finalizing the non-binding document, \"The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012\", which opens with, \"We the Heads of State and Government and high-level representatives\", having met at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 20 to 22 June 2012, with the full participation of civil society, renew our commitment to sustainable development and to ensuring the promotion of an economically, socially and environmentally sustainable future for our planet and for present and future generations.\"<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\">{{Cite report| title =The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012| access-date = 8 April 2020 |date=June 2012| url = https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/733FutureWeWant.pdf}}</ref>\n\n\nThe first draft of the document was released in January 2012 as a result of preliminary intergovernmental discussions and negotiations that had taken place since May 2010.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/>\nA streamlined version of \"The Future We Want\", was released on April 2012 following the second phase of negotiations.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/>\n\nAt the Rio+20 Conference in June 2012, the heads of state of the 192 governments in attendance, renewed their political commitment to sustainable development and declared their commitment to the promotion of a sustainable future through the 49-page nonbinding document,<ref name=\"Gerhardt\"/>  \"The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012.\" The dates June 20 to 22 reflect the three-day meeting of world leaders, the culmination of Rio+20.<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\"/>\n\nThe document largely reaffirms previous action plans like Agenda 21.<ref name=\"slideshare\">{{cite web|author=uncsd2012 |url=http://www.slideshare.net/uncsd2012/the-future-we-want-rio20-outcome-document |title=The Future We Want Rio+20 Outcome Document |publisher=Slideshare.net |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>  \n\nThe document, \"The Future We Want,\" called for the development of [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs), a set of measurable targets aimed at promoting sustainable development globally. It is thought that the SDGs [would] pick up where the Millennium Development Goals leave off and address criticism that the original Goals fail to address the role of the environment in development.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/biores/136257/ |title=Agreement Reached on Weakened Outcome Text as Leaders Arrive for Rio Summit &#124; International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development |publisher=Ictsd.org |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere were eight key recommendations regarding the UN Environment Programme (UNEP) , which included strengthening its governance to potentially become, a \"leading global environmental authority\", through universal membership, increasing its financial resources and strengthening its engagement in key UN coordination bodies.\n\nAccording to a 23 June 2012 ''[[The Guardian]]'' article, nations agreed to explore alternatives to GDP as a measure of wealth that take environmental and social factors into account in an effort to assess and pay for 'environmental services' provided by nature, such as carbon sequestration and habitat protection.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/23/rio-20-earth-summit-document | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Jonathan | last1=Watts | first2=Liz | last2=Ford | title=Rio+20 Earth Summit: campaigners decry final document | date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRecognition that \"fundamental changes in the way societies consume and produce are indispensable for achieving global sustainable development.\" EU officials suggest it could lead to a shift of taxes so workers pay less and polluters and landfill operators pay more.\n\nThe document calls the need to return ocean stocks to sustainable levels \"urgent\" and calls on countries to develop and implement science-based management plans.<ref name=\"slideshare\"/>\n\nAll nations reaffirmed commitments to phase out fossil fuel subsidies.\n\nIn addition to the outcome text, there were over 400 voluntary commitments for sustainable development made by Member States.\n\nAt the African Ministerial Conference on the Environment, 40 African countries agreed to implement \"The Future We Want.\"<ref name=\"Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=42897&Cr=sustainable+development&Cr1= | title=At UN-backed conference, African countries adopt sustainable development measures | publisher=UN News Centre | date=14 September 2012 | accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Leaders in attendance==\n[[File:World Leaders at Rio+20.jpg|thumb|400px|alt=World leaders attending Rio+20|World leaders in attendance at Rio+20]]\n\nA few key global leaders\u2014mostly G20 leaders and namely [[United States President]] [[Barack Obama]], [[German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]], and [[UK Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]]\u2014did not attend the conference and blamed their absence on the ongoing [[European sovereign-debt crisis]]. Their collective absence was seen as a reflection of their administrations' failure to prioritize sustainability issues.<ref name=\"theguardian_20120617\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/11/david-cameron-rio-earth-summit | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=John | last=Vidal | title=David Cameron criticised for skipping Rio+20 Earth summit | date=11 June 2012}}</ref> \"In not attending, the prime minister is sending out a powerful signal that the UK government does not see sustainability as a priority\", Joan Walley, chair of the UK environmental audit committee said to The Guardian.\n\n* {{flagicon|Albania}} Albania \u2013 Prime Minister [[Sali Berisha]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Ambassador Ferit Hoxha's Opinion about Rio +20|url=http://www.cgalbania.com.br/index.php?area=noticia11|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Antigua & Barbuda}} Antigua & Barbuda \u2013 Prime Minister [[Baldwin Spencer]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Antigua and Barbuda Contributes to the Outcome of Rio+20|url=http://www.caribarena.com/antigua/news/latest/100889-antigua-and-barbuda-contributes-to-the-outcome-of-rio-20.html|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} Argentina \u2013 President [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CFK arrives in Brazil to take part at Rio +20 Summit|url=http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/104068/cfk-arrives-in-brazil-to-take-part-at-rio-+20-summit|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=Buenos Aires Herald|date=20 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512125735/http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/104068/cfk-arrives-in-brazil-to-take-part-at-rio-+20-summit|archive-date=12 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \n* {{flagicon|Australia}} Australia \u2013 Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: A Crisis Is a Terrible Thing to Waste|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tina-gerhardt/rio20-earth-summit_b_1619996.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2012|first=Tina|last=Gerhardt}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bolivia}} Bolivia \u2013 President [[Evo Morales]],<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20 summit: Thursday as it happened|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2012/jun/21/rio-20-summit-thursday-live-blog|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 June 2012|location=London|first=Adam|last=Vaughan}}</ref> see Bolivian government proposal [[Harmony with nature]]\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} '''Brazil''' \u2013 '''[[President of Brazil|President]]''' '''[[Dilma Rousseff]]'''<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n* {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} Bulgaria \u2013 President [[Rosen Plevneliev]]\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} Chile \u2013 President [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]]\n* {{flagicon|China}} China \u2013 [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Wen Jiabao]]<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: All eyes on Manmohan Singh, Wen Jiabao|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-20/india/32334846_1_sustainable-development-green-economy-draft|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=20 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Costa Rica}} Costa Rica \u2013 President [[Laura Chinchilla Miranda]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" /> \n* {{flagicon|Denmark}} Denmark \u2013 Prime Minister [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n* {{flagicon|Ecuador}} Ecuador \u2013 President [[Rafael Correa]]<ref name=\"cipamericas\">{{cite web|title=From the Green Economy to Communality|url=http://www.cipamericas.org/archives/7690|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|France}} France \u2013 President [[Francois Hollande]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio+20: France seeks one agenda to end poverty and protect environment|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2012/jun/18/rio20-france-agenda-poverty-environment|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 June 2012|location=London|first=Angelique|last=Chrisafis}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Grenada}} Grenada \u2013 Prime Minister [[Tillman Thomas]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_a\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: Leadership from New Directions|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mark-tercek/rio20-leadership-new_b_1630677.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=28 June 2012|first=Mark|last=Tercek}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Haiti}} Haiti \u2013 President [[Michel Martelly]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Haiti \u2013 Politic : Speeches of President Martelly to Rio+20|url=http://www.haitilibre.com/en/news-5957-haiti-politic-speeches-of-president-martelly-to-rio+20-audio.html|publisher=Haiti Libre|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|India}} India \u2013 Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]]<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\" />\n* {{flagicon|Indonesia}} Indonesia \u2013 President [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono|Susilo Yudhoyono]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_a\" />\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} Iran \u2013 President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n* {{flagicon|Lithuania}} Lithuania \u2013 President [[Dalia Grybauskait\u0117]]\n* {{flagicon|Nepal}} Nepal \u2013 Prime Minister [[Baburam Bhattarai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio+20 a generational opportunity' says PM|url=http://thehimalayantimes.com/rssReference.php?headline=Rio%2B20+a+generational+opportunity%26sbquo%3B+says+PM&NewsID=336994|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Himalayan Times|date=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Nigeria}} Nigeria \u2013 President [[Goodluck Jonathan]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan, Rio 20 and the Environment|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/jonathan-rio-20-and-the-environment/118744/|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=This Day|date=26 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Norway}} Norway \u2013 Prime Minister [[Jens Stoltenberg]]<ref>{{cite web|title='Godmother Gro' hailed in Rio|url=http://www.newsinenglish.no/2012/06/20/godmother-gro-hailed-in-rio/|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Portugal}} Portugal \u2013 Prime Minister [[Pedro Passos Coelho]]<ref>{{cite web|title=World Leaders to Tour Region after G20 and Rio+20|url=http://www.americasquarterly.org/node/3715|work=Americas Quarterly|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Russia}} Russia \u2013 President [[Dmitry Medvedev]]<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n* {{flagicon|South Africa}} South Africa \u2013 President [[Jacob Zuma]]<ref>{{cite news|title=South Africa: President Zuma Returns From Rio+20 Conference|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201206240345.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|date=24 June 2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} South Korea \u2013 President [[Lee Myung bak]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lee champions green growth at Rio+20 meeting|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2012/06/113_113543.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Korea Times|date=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain \u2013 Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]]<ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20 summit: Opening day live blog|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2012/jun/20/rio-20-earth-summit-live-blog|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 June 2012|location=London|first=Adam|last=Vaughan}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} Sri Lanka \u2013 President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio 20 proves a damp squib of a summit|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/120624/news/rio20-proves-a-damp-squib-of-a-summit-4176.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Sunday Times|date=24 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden \u2013 Prime Minister [[Fredrik Reinfeldt]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Speech by Prime Minister Fredrik Reinfeldt at Rio +20 Summit on Sustainable Development|url=http://www.government.se/sb/d/7966/a/195667|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Turkmenistan}} Turkmenistan \u2013 President [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} Uruguay \u2013 President [[Jose Mujica]]<ref name=\"cipamericas\" />\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} Zimbabwe \u2013 President [[Robert Mugabe]]<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\namong others\n\n{{clear left}}\n==Environmental and Indigenous Rights Activists==[[File:Rio+20 statue of liberty and Dilma Rousseff.JPG|thumb|Demonstration at Rio+20. Picture shows effigy of Brazilian President [[Dilma Rousseff]] with a chainsaw and embracing a replica of the Statue of Liberty.]]\n\nActivists took initiative at Rio+20 by staging numerous protests.  Activists joined forces to stand up to what they said was exploitation and degradation of the [[Earth]], as well as the negation of the rights of [[indigenous peoples]]. ''[[National Geographic]]'' said that activists that support protecting the environment, are particularly relevant in [[Brazil]], as [[deforestation]] threatens [[Amazon Basin|Amazonian]] ethnic groups everyday.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wallace |first=Scott |title=Last of the Amazon|url=http://environment.nationalgeographic.com/environment/habitats/last-of-amazon/ |work=National Geographic |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to holding signs and shouting chants, the crowds took a theatric route to convey their messages. Firstly, they poked at [[Brazilian President]] [[Dilma Rousseff]], claiming she has given in to the global North's corporate hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/22/megastars-of-the-earth-summit/|title=Stars of the Earth Summit|first=Taylor|last=Barnes|date=4 August 1692|website=Green Blog}}</ref>  Rousseff's controversy has arisen over her steadfast desire to further industrialize Brazil, and its economy. Additionally, the crowds assembled for a ritual and symbolic \"tearing up\" of the plenary's negotiated text,<ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathan Watts, in Rio de Janeiro |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/21/rio-20-protesters-text-agreement |title=The Guardian June 21, 2012 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> conveying their disapproval.\n\nThousands of non-governmental organizations (NGOs) gathered at the Flamengo Park in Rio. They criticized the draft negotiating text, particularly for its failure to mention planetary boundaries or nuclear energy, in light of the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima disaster]] in [[Japan]].<ref name=\"Gerhardt\"/> Organizations, such as [[Greenpeace]] and the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]], as well as members of indigenous communities, activists and artists participated. The Danish artist [[Jens Galschi\u00f8t]], the leader of the group [[AIDOH]], and the Group 92 used his Freedom to Pollute sculptures to focus on global warming and its resulting increased flow of refugees. About 20,000 flyers about Freedom to Pollute were distributed during [[Rio+20]] and a related television program was produced in [[Denmark]].\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Demonstration against Ahmadinejad in Rio.jpg|100px|right||Demonstration against the President of Iran [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]].]]There were some demonstrations protesting the participation of the President of Iran [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] along with the Iranian delegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1477999-ahmadinejad-otra-vez-en-america-latina |title=Ahmadinejad, otra vez en Am\u00e9rica latina |publisher=Lanacion.com.ar |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irandailybrief.com/2012/05/30/iranian-president-to-attend-rio20-conference/ |title=Iranian president to attend Rio+20 Conference \" Iran Daily Brief |publisher=Irandailybrief.com |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The controversy of Iranian attendance at the summit surrounds the fact that Iran has serious environmental issues, which it has refused to address, continuing human rights violations and is refusing to cooperate with the [[IAEA]] over its contentious nuclear program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/globo-news/jornal-das-dez/videos/t/todos-os-videos/v/iraniano-acredita-que-ahmadinejad-vem-a-rio-20-para-mostrar-que-o-ira-tem-amigos/1971439/ |title=Iraniano acredita que Ahmadinejad vem \u00e0 Rio +20 para mostrar que o Ir\u00e3 tem amigos \u2013 GloboNews \u2013 V\u00eddeos do Jornal das Dez \u2013 Cat\u00e1logo de V\u00eddeos |publisher=G1.globo.com |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> Ahmadinejad was met with demonstrations, attended by thousands of people, on his 20 June arrival in Rio,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/8136098@N05/7388334902/ |title=Activists walk through Rio, demonstrating against the presence of the Iranian delegation at the summit |publisher=Flickr.com |date=17 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/8136098@N05/7388322554/ |title=Activists walk through Rio, demonstrating against the presence of the Iranian delegation at the summit |publisher=Flickr.com |date=17 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> \nwith some protesters waving banners with the slogan \"Ahmadinejad go home\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Rozen |first=Laura |url=http://backchannel.al-monitor.com/index.php/2012/06/blame-it-on-rio-israeli-delegate-says-irans-president-waved-at-them/ |title=Blame it on Rio? Israeli delegate says Iran's Ahmadinejad waved at them &#124; The Back Channel |publisher=Backchannel.al-monitor.com |date=25 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Participation by Civil Societies==\n[[File:Rio-hindi.PNG|thumb|RIO +20 Logo in Hindi created by CCLP Worldwide Team]]\n\nDuring RIO +20 event and preparatory events [[UNCSD]] included Civil Societies invited to organize side events, promote the RIO event, submit literature and help the Rio secretariat with translation work. The logo and promotion of RIO +20 was available in languages used in [[United Nations]]. Civil societies also translated the logo image and literature in other local and National languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/index.php?page=view&nr=1070&type=230&menu=38 |title=Rio+20 : The Seventh issue of the magazine |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=11 April 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==ProjectEarth Network==\nEcology and Environment Inc., a New York-based Environmental Engineering and Consultation company partnered with UNCSD to create Project Earth Network, an online platform where schools around the world could showcase their remarkable environmental projects. In coordination with the Rio+20 event, the platform hosted a World Environment Day Global School Contest in which 7th graders at the International School of Ulaanbaatar (ISU) in Mongolia were declared the Global Winners for their awareness campaign on the environmental impact of plastic shopping bags, including research on plastic bag manufacturing processes, development of videos documenting plastic bag waste, and a school presentation at which reusable cloth shopping bags were sold to approximately 50 percent of the community.\n\nSarasota, Fla.'s Brookside Middle School won in the World Environment Day contest's North American sub-category for its mangrove propagule growth project while International School of Brussels in Belgium won the European sub-category, for their creation of a sustainable food source and composting program. The Middle-Eastern sub-category winner was [[Hridith Sudev]], a seventh grader from [[Indian School Salalah]] in Oman for his organization, '[[Project GreenWorld International]]' which helped promote sustainable awareness across the region through interactive projects. Hridith Sudev later went on to become an inventor and the organization has become a global environmental presence. The World Environment Day contest followed an Earth Day \"Green Schools\" contest regionally focused toward 6th to 12th grade students in the Western New York area.\n\nThe idea behind the platform was to encourage sustainability in students across the world. Despite the huge response, the platform was taken down two years later due to technical and economic constraints but has since remained as a positive legacy through the activities of students who were first recognized by the network.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Earth Summit]]\n** [[Agenda 21]]\n** [[Rio Declaration on Environment and Development]]\n* [[Durban III]] The conference opened on 22 September 2011\n* [[Planetary boundaries#United Nations endorsement|Planetary boundaries]]\n* [[Sustainable Development Goals]]\n* [[The United Nations Ocean Conference]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110420002837/http://www.uncsd2012.org/ United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development]\n* [[Brundtland Report|Our Common Future: Report of the World Commission on Environment and Development]]\n** [http://rio20.ebc.com.br/memoria/ Videos, photos and information about the Summit in Brazil]\n** [http://rio20.net/en/ Rio+20 Portal. Building the Peoples Summit]\n* [http://www.environmentmagazine.org/Archives/Back%20Issues/2012/March-April%202012/Rio_abstract.html Rio + 20: An Endangered Species?], March/April 2012 journal Environment\n* [http://www.adb.org/features/12-things-know-2012-sustainable-development Rio+20 and Sustainable Development: 12 Things to Know] Asian Development Bank\n* [https://www.un.org/en/sustainablefuture/ The Future We Want]\n* [http://www.earthsummit2012.org Earth Summit 2012]\n* [https://ecsdev.org/images/conference/5th-ICSD-2017-Program.pdf International Conference on Sustainable Development]\n* [http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415540254/ Only One Earth \u2013 the Long Road via Rio to Sustainable Development], the history from Stockholm to Rio by [[Felix Dodds]], Michael Strauss with [[Maurice Strong]]\n\n{{Sustainability}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics}}\n\n{{coord|22.9098|S|43.1763|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United Nations Conference On Sustainable Development}}\n[[Category:United Nations conferences]]\n[[Category:2012 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:2012 conferences]]\n[[Category:2012 in the environment]]\n[[Category:Environmental conferences]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Brazil]]\n[[Category:2012 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2010s in Rio de Janeiro]]\n[[Category:June 2012 events in South America]]\n[[Category:Brazil and the United Nations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development\n| native_name  = \n| logo         =\n| logo_caption =\n| image        = <!--DO NOT include \"File:\" part of image name\n                 (different from above because of merger with\n                 Template:Infobox festival)-->Rio+20_logo.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = \n| date         = 13\u201322 June 2012<ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\"/><ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/>\n| prev         = [[Earth Summit|Earth Summit 1992]]<br />[[Earth Summit 2002]]\n| next         = \n| frequency    =\n| location     = [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| years_active =\n| first        = <!--\"founded=\" also works-->\n| participants =\n| attendance   =\n| genre        =\n| budget       =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = <!--\"organized=\" also works-->\n| website      = [https://web.archive.org/web/20110420002837/http://www.uncsd2012.org/ uncsd2012]\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n\nThe '''United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development''' ('''UNCSD'''), also known as '''Rio 2012''', '''Rio+20''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8\u0281i.u \u02c8maj\u0292 \u02c8v\u0129t\u0283i}}), or '''Earth Summit 2012''' was the third international conference on [[sustainable development]] aimed at reconciling the economic and environmental goals of the global community. Hosted by [[Brazil]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] from 13 to 22 June 2012,<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/><ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\"/> Rio+20 was a 20-year follow-up to the 1992 [[Earth Summit|United Nations Conference on Environment and Development]] (UNCED) held in the same city, and the 10th anniversary of the 2002 [[Earth Summit 2002|World Summit on Sustainable Development]] (WSSD) in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nThe ten-day mega-summit, which culminated in a three-day high-level UN conference, was organized by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs and included participation from 192 UN member states \u2013 including 57 Heads of State and 31 Heads of Government, private sector companies, NGOs and other groups. The decision to hold the conference was made by UN General Assembly Resolution A/RES/64/236 on 24 December 2009. It was intended to be a high-level conference, including heads of state and government or other representatives and resulting in a focused political document designed to shape global environmental policy.<ref name=\"about.html\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/about.html |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=22 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140818215812/http://www.uncsd2012.org/about.html |archivedate=18 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the final three days of the Conference, from 20 to 22 June 2012, world leaders and representatives met for intense meetings which culminated in finalizing the non-binding document, \"The World We Want\" which opens with \"We the Heads of State and Government and high-level representatives\", having met at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 20 to 22 June 2012, with the full participation of civil society, renew our commitment to sustainable development and to ensuring the promotion of an economically, socially and environmentally sustainable future for our planet and for present and future generations.\"<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nIn 1992, the first conference of its kind, the [[United Nations Conference on Environment and Development]] ([[UNCED]]), commonly referred to as the Rio Conference or Earth Summit, succeeded in raising public awareness of the need to integrate environment and development. The conference drew 109 heads of state to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], to address what were dubbed urgent problems of environmental protection and socio-economic development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/esa/earthsummit/ |title=United Nations Earth Summit+5 |publisher=United Nations |date=27 June 1997 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The Earth Summit influenced subsequent UN conferences, including Rio+20 and set the global green agenda. \"The World Conference on Human Rights, for example, focused on the right of people to a healthy environment and the right to development; controversial demands that had met with resistance from some Member States until the Earth Summit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/geninfo/bp/enviro.html/ |title=Earth_Summit |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nMajor outcomes of the conference include the [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC) \u2014a climate-change agreement that led to the [[Kyoto Protocol]], [[Agenda 21]], the [[United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity]] (CBD) and the [[United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification]] (UNCCD). It also created new international institutions, among them the Commission on Sustainable Development, tasked with the follow-up to the Rio Conference and led to the reform of the [[Global Environment Facility]].<ref name=\"isfd.html\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/isfd.html |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=29 July 2011 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nTen years later, [[Earth Summit 2002]] informally nicknamed Rio+10 was held in Johannesburg, South Africa with the goal of again bringing together leaders from government, business and NGOs to agree on a range of measures toward similar goals. At Rio+10, [[sustainable development]] was recognized as an overarching goal for institutions at the national, regional and international levels. There, the need to enhance the integration of sustainable development in the activities of all relevant United Nations agencies, programs and funds was highlighted. The discussion also encompassed the role of institutions in stepping up efforts to bridge the gap between the international financial institutions and the multilateral development banks and the rest of the UN system.<ref name=\"isfd.html\"/>\n\nMajor outcomes of that conference include the [[Johannesburg Declaration]] and almost 300 international partnership initiatives meant to help achieve the [[Millennium Development Goals]].\n\n== Objectives ==\n\nThe conference had three objectives\u2014to secure renewed political commitment for sustainable development, to assess the progress and implementation gaps in meeting previous commitments, and to address new and emerging challenges.\n\n== Conference themes ==\nThe official discussions had two main themes, how to build a [[green economy]] to achieve sustainable development and lift people out of poverty, including support for developing countries that will allow them to find a green path for development; and how to improve international coordination for sustainable development by building an institutional framework.\n\n== Rio+20 formal preparatory process ==\n\nIn the months leading up to the beginning of the conference, negotiators held frequent informal consultations at UN headquarters in [[New York City]], and in the two weeks before the conference was scheduled to begin, they managed to reach consensus on the sensitive language in the then proposed outcome document for the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/136199/ |title=Agreement Reached on Weakened Outcome Text as Leaders Arrive for Rio Summit &#124; International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development |publisher=Ictsd.org |date=31 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to historian [[Felix Dodds]] in his 2014 co-authored 2014 book entitled, ''From Rio+20 to a New Development Agenda: Building a Bridge to a Sustainable Future'', the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development\u2014Rio+20 formal preparatory process, can be divided into three phases. \n\nPhase one took place from May 2010 to January 2012\u2014when preliminary intergovernmental discussions and negotiations began, and national, regional, and local level preparations were being made. This stage ended with the January 2012 publication of the draft document, \"The Future We Want\"<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\">{{Cite book| edition = 1| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 978-0-415-71654-3| last1 = Dodds| first1 = Felix| last2 = Laguna-Celis| first2 = Jorges| last3 = Thompson| first3 = Liz| title = From Rio+20 to a New Development Agenda| location = New York| date = 7 February 2014 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=CBSkAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=preparatory+process+Rio%2B20+13+June+to+15+2012&source=bl&ots=lXHjNwHBic&sig=ACfU3U2k9HsNvI0FfSSA-2ne8uGPN3CdeQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFnd29xtnoAhVBj54KHasTDH4Q6AEwAHoECAwQLA#v=onepage&q=13%20June%20to%2015%202012&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/17/world/americas/brazils-president-dilma-rousseff-faces-defining-decision-over-forest-bill.html|title=Brazil's Leader Faces Defining Decision on Bill Relaxing Protection of Forests | work=The New York Times | first=Simon|last=Romero|date=16 May 2012}}</ref> The 1st Preparatory Committee was held from 16\u201318 May 2010, immediately after the conclusion of the eighteenth session and the first meeting of the nineteenth session of the [[Commission on Sustainable Development]]. The 1st Intersessional\u2014which was not a negotiation session \u2013 featured panel discussions, from academia, non-governmental organizations as well as Delegates and UN system representatives\u2014was held from 10\u201311 January 2011 at UN Headquarters, [[New York City|New York]]. The 2nd Preparatory Committee was held from 7\u20138 March 2011, at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York, immediately following the Intergovernmental Policy Meeting for the 19th Session of the [[Commission on Sustainable Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=72&Itemid=123 |title=Rio+20 \u2013 United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=22 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The 2nd Intersessional was held from 15\u201316 December 2011 at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110728143834/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/index.php?page=view&type=13&nr=42&menu=46 ]</ref>\n\nPhase two\u2014from March 2012 to April 2012\u2014began with the first informal negotiations and concluded with the April 2012 release of co-chairs streamline text of \"The Future We Want\".<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/> The 3rd Intersessional was held from 5\u20137 March 2012 at [[United Nations Headquarters]] in New York.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111111053059/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/index.php?page=view&type=13&nr=46&menu=46 ]</ref>\n\nPhase three\u2014from April 9, 2012 to June 15, 2012\u2014began with the second round of negotiations starting on April 9, 2012, and ending with the June 15, 2012 closing of the Third Preparatory Committee meeting, when negotiators were already in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/> Th three-day intense meetings with hundreds of \"heads of states from around the world\" met in Rio de Janeiro after the the 3rd Preparatory Meeting had concluded.<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\"/>\n\n==United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development ==\n\nAccording to a 13 June 2012 ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' article, the \"giant, 10-day-long\" Conference underway in Rio de Janeiro which would end on June 22, 2012, was \"expected to draw 50,000 participants, including delegates, environmental activists, business leaders, and indigenous groups.\" For the final three days of the conference, \"about 130 heads of state from around the world were expected to be present.\"<ref name=\"Wa_Po_20220613\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/giant-10-day-long-un-conference-on-sustainable-development-gets-underway-in-rio-de-janeiro/2012/06/13/gJQAbPGVaV_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614083725/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/giant-10-day-long-un-conference-on-sustainable-development-gets-underway-in-rio-de-janeiro/2012/06/13/gJQAbPGVaV_story.html|archive-date=14 June 2012|title=Giant, 10-day-long UN conference on sustainable development gets underway in Rio de Janeiro|work=[[The Washington Post]] via [[Associated Press]]|date=13 June 2012|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"IISD_SummaryRio20\">{{Cite journal| journal = Earth Negotiations Bulletin |volume=27 |number=51 |publisher=[[International Institute for Sustainable Development]] (IISD) |date=25 June 2012|series=A Reporting Service for Environment and Development Negotiations (UNCSD) |title=Summary of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development: 13-22 June 2012| access-date = 8 April 2020| url = https://enb.iisd.org/download/pdf/enb2751e.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBilled as the biggest UN event ever organized\u2014with 15,000 soldiers and police guarding about 130 heads of state and government, from 192 countries, and the more than 45,000 individuals gathered in [[Rio de Janeiro]]\u2014the 10-day mega-conference was intended to be a high-level international gathering organized to re-direct and renew global political commitment to the three dimensions of sustainable development: economic growth, social improvement and environmental protection; focusing on reducing poverty while promoting  jobs growth, clean energy and more fair, sustainable uses of resources; goals first established at Earth Summit in 1992.<ref name=\"about.html\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/newsletter.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=4 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825072833/http://www.uncsd2012.org/rio20/newsletter.html |archivedate=25 August 2012 }}</ref> \n<ref>[http://www.environment.gov.au/rio/index.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724110850/http://www.environment.gov.au/rio/index.html |date=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe conference centered around Agenda 21, the outcome document from Earth Summit 1992. That document was considered revolutionary in that it essentially created the term sustainable development and created the global environmental agenda for the next 20 years. The representatives of participating governments gathered in Rio to discuss what was then the draft text of the outcome document.\n\nRio+20 sought to secure affirmations for the political commitments made at past Earth Summits and set the global environmental agenda for the next 20 years by assessing progress towards the goals set forth in Agenda 21 and implementation gaps therein, and discussing new and emerging issues.\n<ref name=\"Gerhardt\">{{Cite news|last=Gerhardt|first=Tina|date=20 June 2012|title=Rio+20 Kicks Off|url=http://www.progressive.org/rio_20_kicks_off.html|work=[[The Progressive]]}}</ref> The UN wanted Rio to endorse a UN \"green economy roadmap\", with environmental goals, targets and deadlines, whereas developing countries preferred establishing new \"sustainable development goals\" to better protect the environment, guarantee food and power to the poorest, and alleviate poverty.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/19/rio-20-earth-summit-1992-2012 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=John | last=Vidal | title=Rio+20: Earth summit dawns with stormier clouds than in 1992 | date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRio+20 attracted many protests, and more than 500 parallel events, exhibitions, presentations, fairs and announcements as a wide range of diverse groups struggled to take advantage of the conference in order to gain international attention. The British online newspaper, The Guardian reported that, \"Downtown Rio de Janeiro was partly shut-down as an estimated 50,000 protesters, some of whom were naked, took to the streets.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/video/2012/jun/21/rio20-summit-opens-protests-video | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Rio+20 summit opens amid protests \u2013 video | date=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== The future we want ===\nFrom 20 to 22 June 2012, world leaders and representatives met for intense meetings which culminated in finalizing the non-binding document, \"The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012\", which opens with, \"We the Heads of State and Government and high-level representatives\", having met at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 20 to 22 June 2012, with the full participation of civil society, renew our commitment to sustainable development and to ensuring the promotion of an economically, socially and environmentally sustainable future for our planet and for present and future generations.\"<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\">{{Cite report| title =The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012| access-date = 8 April 2020 |date=June 2012| url = https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/733FutureWeWant.pdf}}</ref>\n\n\nThe first draft of the document was released in January 2012 as a result of preliminary intergovernmental discussions and negotiations that had taken place since May 2010.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/>\nA streamlined version of \"The Future We Want\", was released on April 2012 following the second phase of negotiations.<ref name=\"Dodds_Laguna_Thompson_Rio_2012\"/>\n\nAt the Rio+20 Conference in June 2012, the heads of state of the 192 governments in attendance, renewed their political commitment to sustainable development and declared their commitment to the promotion of a sustainable future through the 49-page nonbinding document,<ref name=\"Gerhardt\"/>  \"The Future We Want: Outcome document of the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, 20\u201322 June 2012.\" The dates June 20 to 22 reflect the three-day meeting of world leaders, the culmination of Rio+20.<ref name=\"UN_FutureWeWant_202006_20-22\"/>\n\nThe document largely reaffirms previous action plans like Agenda 21.<ref name=\"slideshare\">{{cite web|author=uncsd2012 |url=http://www.slideshare.net/uncsd2012/the-future-we-want-rio20-outcome-document |title=The Future We Want Rio+20 Outcome Document |publisher=Slideshare.net |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>  \n\nThe document, \"The Future We Want,\" called for the development of [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs), a set of measurable targets aimed at promoting sustainable development globally. It is thought that the SDGs [would] pick up where the Millennium Development Goals leave off and address criticism that the original Goals fail to address the role of the environment in development.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ictsd.org/i/news/biores/136257/ |title=Agreement Reached on Weakened Outcome Text as Leaders Arrive for Rio Summit &#124; International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development |publisher=Ictsd.org |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere were eight key recommendations regarding the UN Environment Programme (UNEP) , which included strengthening its governance to potentially become, a \"leading global environmental authority\", through universal membership, increasing its financial resources and strengthening its engagement in key UN coordination bodies.\n\nAccording to a 23 June 2012 ''[[The Guardian]]'' article, nations agreed to explore alternatives to GDP as a measure of wealth that take environmental and social factors into account in an effort to assess and pay for 'environmental services' provided by nature, such as carbon sequestration and habitat protection.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/23/rio-20-earth-summit-document | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Jonathan | last1=Watts | first2=Liz | last2=Ford | title=Rio+20 Earth Summit: campaigners decry final document | date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nRecognition that \"fundamental changes in the way societies consume and produce are indispensable for achieving global sustainable development.\" EU officials suggest it could lead to a shift of taxes so workers pay less and polluters and landfill operators pay more.\n\nThe document calls the need to return ocean stocks to sustainable levels \"urgent\" and calls on countries to develop and implement science-based management plans.<ref name=\"slideshare\"/>\n\nAll nations reaffirmed commitments to phase out fossil fuel subsidies.\n\nIn addition to the outcome text, there were over 400 voluntary commitments for sustainable development made by Member States.\n\nAt the African Ministerial Conference on the Environment, 40 African countries agreed to implement \"The Future We Want.\"<ref name=\"Africa\">{{cite web | url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=42897&Cr=sustainable+development&Cr1= | title=At UN-backed conference, African countries adopt sustainable development measures | publisher=UN News Centre | date=14 September 2012 | accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Leaders in attendance==\n[[File:World Leaders at Rio+20.jpg|thumb|400px|alt=World leaders attending Rio+20|World leaders in attendance at Rio+20]]\n\nA few key global leaders\u2014mostly G20 leaders and namely [[United States President]] [[Barack Obama]], [[German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]], and [[UK Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]]\u2014did not attend the conference and blamed their absence on the ongoing [[European sovereign-debt crisis]]. Their collective absence was seen as a reflection of their administrations' failure to prioritize sustainability issues.<ref name=\"theguardian_20120617\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/11/david-cameron-rio-earth-summit | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=John | last=Vidal | title=David Cameron criticised for skipping Rio+20 Earth summit | date=11 June 2012}}</ref> \"In not attending, the prime minister is sending out a powerful signal that the UK government does not see sustainability as a priority\", Joan Walley, chair of the UK environmental audit committee said to The Guardian.\n\n* {{flagicon|Albania}} Albania \u2013 Prime Minister [[Sali Berisha]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Ambassador Ferit Hoxha's Opinion about Rio +20|url=http://www.cgalbania.com.br/index.php?area=noticia11|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Antigua & Barbuda}} Antigua & Barbuda \u2013 Prime Minister [[Baldwin Spencer]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Antigua and Barbuda Contributes to the Outcome of Rio+20|url=http://www.caribarena.com/antigua/news/latest/100889-antigua-and-barbuda-contributes-to-the-outcome-of-rio-20.html|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} Argentina \u2013 President [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]]<ref>{{cite news|title=CFK arrives in Brazil to take part at Rio +20 Summit|url=http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/104068/cfk-arrives-in-brazil-to-take-part-at-rio-+20-summit|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=Buenos Aires Herald|date=20 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512125735/http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/104068/cfk-arrives-in-brazil-to-take-part-at-rio-+20-summit|archive-date=12 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \n* {{flagicon|Australia}} Australia \u2013 Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: A Crisis Is a Terrible Thing to Waste|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tina-gerhardt/rio20-earth-summit_b_1619996.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=25 June 2012|first=Tina|last=Gerhardt}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bolivia}} Bolivia \u2013 President [[Evo Morales]],<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20 summit: Thursday as it happened|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2012/jun/21/rio-20-summit-thursday-live-blog|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 June 2012|location=London|first=Adam|last=Vaughan}}</ref> see Bolivian government proposal [[Harmony with nature]]\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} '''Brazil''' \u2013 '''[[President of Brazil|President]]''' '''[[Dilma Rousseff]]'''<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n* {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} Bulgaria \u2013 President [[Rosen Plevneliev]]\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} Chile \u2013 President [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]]\n* {{flagicon|China}} China \u2013 [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Wen Jiabao]]<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: All eyes on Manmohan Singh, Wen Jiabao|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-20/india/32334846_1_sustainable-development-green-economy-draft|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=20 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Costa Rica}} Costa Rica \u2013 President [[Laura Chinchilla Miranda]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" /> \n* {{flagicon|Denmark}} Denmark \u2013 Prime Minister [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n* {{flagicon|Ecuador}} Ecuador \u2013 President [[Rafael Correa]]<ref name=\"cipamericas\">{{cite web|title=From the Green Economy to Communality|url=http://www.cipamericas.org/archives/7690|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|France}} France \u2013 President [[Francois Hollande]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio+20: France seeks one agenda to end poverty and protect environment|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2012/jun/18/rio20-france-agenda-poverty-environment|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 June 2012|location=London|first=Angelique|last=Chrisafis}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Grenada}} Grenada \u2013 Prime Minister [[Tillman Thomas]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_a\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20: Leadership from New Directions|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mark-tercek/rio20-leadership-new_b_1630677.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=28 June 2012|first=Mark|last=Tercek}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Haiti}} Haiti \u2013 President [[Michel Martelly]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Haiti \u2013 Politic : Speeches of President Martelly to Rio+20|url=http://www.haitilibre.com/en/news-5957-haiti-politic-speeches-of-president-martelly-to-rio+20-audio.html|publisher=Haiti Libre|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|India}} India \u2013 Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]]<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\" />\n* {{flagicon|Indonesia}} Indonesia \u2013 President [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono|Susilo Yudhoyono]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_a\" />\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} Iran \u2013 President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n* {{flagicon|Lithuania}} Lithuania \u2013 President [[Dalia Grybauskait\u0117]]\n* {{flagicon|Nepal}} Nepal \u2013 Prime Minister [[Baburam Bhattarai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio+20 a generational opportunity' says PM|url=http://thehimalayantimes.com/rssReference.php?headline=Rio%2B20+a+generational+opportunity%26sbquo%3B+says+PM&NewsID=336994|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Himalayan Times|date=22 June 2012}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Nigeria}} Nigeria \u2013 President [[Goodluck Jonathan]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan, Rio 20 and the Environment|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/jonathan-rio-20-and-the-environment/118744/|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=This Day|date=26 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Norway}} Norway \u2013 Prime Minister [[Jens Stoltenberg]]<ref>{{cite web|title='Godmother Gro' hailed in Rio|url=http://www.newsinenglish.no/2012/06/20/godmother-gro-hailed-in-rio/|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Portugal}} Portugal \u2013 Prime Minister [[Pedro Passos Coelho]]<ref>{{cite web|title=World Leaders to Tour Region after G20 and Rio+20|url=http://www.americasquarterly.org/node/3715|work=Americas Quarterly|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Russia}} Russia \u2013 President [[Dmitry Medvedev]]<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n* {{flagicon|South Africa}} South Africa \u2013 President [[Jacob Zuma]]<ref>{{cite news|title=South Africa: President Zuma Returns From Rio+20 Conference|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201206240345.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|date=24 June 2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} South Korea \u2013 President [[Lee Myung bak]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lee champions green growth at Rio+20 meeting|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2012/06/113_113543.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Korea Times|date=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain \u2013 Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]]<ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite news|title=Rio+20 summit: Opening day live blog|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2012/jun/20/rio-20-earth-summit-live-blog|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 June 2012|location=London|first=Adam|last=Vaughan}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} Sri Lanka \u2013 President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Rio 20 proves a damp squib of a summit|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/120624/news/rio20-proves-a-damp-squib-of-a-summit-4176.html|accessdate=30 April 2013|newspaper=The Sunday Times|date=24 June 2012}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden \u2013 Prime Minister [[Fredrik Reinfeldt]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Speech by Prime Minister Fredrik Reinfeldt at Rio +20 Summit on Sustainable Development|url=http://www.government.se/sb/d/7966/a/195667|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|Turkmenistan}} Turkmenistan \u2013 President [[Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow]]\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} Uruguay \u2013 President [[Jose Mujica]]<ref name=\"cipamericas\" />\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} Zimbabwe \u2013 President [[Robert Mugabe]]<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\namong others\n\n{{clear left}}\n==Environmental and Indigenous Rights Activists==[[File:Rio+20 statue of liberty and Dilma Rousseff.JPG|thumb|Demonstration at Rio+20. Picture shows effigy of Brazilian President [[Dilma Rousseff]] with a chainsaw and embracing a replica of the Statue of Liberty.]]\n\nActivists took initiative at Rio+20 by staging numerous protests.  Activists joined forces to stand up to what they said was exploitation and degradation of the [[Earth]], as well as the negation of the rights of [[indigenous peoples]]. ''[[National Geographic]]'' said that activists that support protecting the environment, are particularly relevant in [[Brazil]], as [[deforestation]] threatens [[Amazon Basin|Amazonian]] ethnic groups everyday.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wallace |first=Scott |title=Last of the Amazon|url=http://environment.nationalgeographic.com/environment/habitats/last-of-amazon/ |work=National Geographic |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to holding signs and shouting chants, the crowds took a theatric route to convey their messages. Firstly, they poked at [[Brazilian President]] [[Dilma Rousseff]], claiming she has given in to the global North's corporate hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/22/megastars-of-the-earth-summit/|title=Stars of the Earth Summit|first=Taylor|last=Barnes|date=4 August 1692|website=Green Blog}}</ref>  Rousseff's controversy has arisen over her steadfast desire to further industrialize Brazil, and its economy. Additionally, the crowds assembled for a ritual and symbolic \"tearing up\" of the plenary's negotiated text,<ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathan Watts, in Rio de Janeiro |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/jun/21/rio-20-protesters-text-agreement |title=The Guardian June 21, 2012 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> conveying their disapproval.\n\nThousands of non-governmental organizations (NGOs) gathered at the Flamengo Park in Rio. They criticized the draft negotiating text, particularly for its failure to mention planetary boundaries or nuclear energy, in light of the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima disaster]] in [[Japan]].<ref name=\"Gerhardt\"/> Organizations, such as [[Greenpeace]] and the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]], as well as members of indigenous communities, activists and artists participated. The Danish artist [[Jens Galschi\u00f8t]], the leader of the group [[AIDOH]], and the Group 92 used his Freedom to Pollute sculptures to focus on global warming and its resulting increased flow of refugees. About 20,000 flyers about Freedom to Pollute were distributed during [[Rio+20]] and a related television program was produced in [[Denmark]].\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Demonstration against Ahmadinejad in Rio.jpg|100px|right||Demonstration against the President of Iran [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]].]]There were some demonstrations protesting the participation of the President of Iran [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] along with the Iranian delegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1477999-ahmadinejad-otra-vez-en-america-latina |title=Ahmadinejad, otra vez en Am\u00e9rica latina |publisher=Lanacion.com.ar |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irandailybrief.com/2012/05/30/iranian-president-to-attend-rio20-conference/ |title=Iranian president to attend Rio+20 Conference \" Iran Daily Brief |publisher=Irandailybrief.com |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The controversy of Iranian attendance at the summit surrounds the fact that Iran has serious environmental issues, which it has refused to address, continuing human rights violations and is refusing to cooperate with the [[IAEA]] over its contentious nuclear program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/globo-news/jornal-das-dez/videos/t/todos-os-videos/v/iraniano-acredita-que-ahmadinejad-vem-a-rio-20-para-mostrar-que-o-ira-tem-amigos/1971439/ |title=Iraniano acredita que Ahmadinejad vem \u00e0 Rio +20 para mostrar que o Ir\u00e3 tem amigos \u2013 GloboNews \u2013 V\u00eddeos do Jornal das Dez \u2013 Cat\u00e1logo de V\u00eddeos |publisher=G1.globo.com |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> Ahmadinejad was met with demonstrations, attended by thousands of people, on his 20 June arrival in Rio,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/8136098@N05/7388334902/ |title=Activists walk through Rio, demonstrating against the presence of the Iranian delegation at the summit |publisher=Flickr.com |date=17 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/8136098@N05/7388322554/ |title=Activists walk through Rio, demonstrating against the presence of the Iranian delegation at the summit |publisher=Flickr.com |date=17 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> \nwith some protesters waving banners with the slogan \"Ahmadinejad go home\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Rozen |first=Laura |url=http://backchannel.al-monitor.com/index.php/2012/06/blame-it-on-rio-israeli-delegate-says-irans-president-waved-at-them/ |title=Blame it on Rio? Israeli delegate says Iran's Ahmadinejad waved at them &#124; The Back Channel |publisher=Backchannel.al-monitor.com |date=25 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Participation by Civil Societies==\n[[File:Rio-hindi.PNG|thumb|RIO +20 Logo in Hindi created by CCLP Worldwide Team]]\n\nDuring RIO +20 event and preparatory events [[UNCSD]] included Civil Societies invited to organize side events, promote the RIO event, submit literature and help the Rio secretariat with translation work. The logo and promotion of RIO +20 was available in languages used in [[United Nations]]. Civil societies also translated the logo image and literature in other local and National languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uncsd2012.org/index.php?page=view&nr=1070&type=230&menu=38 |title=Rio+20 : The Seventh issue of the magazine |publisher=Uncsd2012.org |date=11 April 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==ProjectEarth Network==\nEcology and Environment Inc., a New York-based Environmental Engineering and Consultation company partnered with UNCSD to create Project Earth Network, an online platform where schools around the world could showcase their remarkable environmental projects. In coordination with the Rio+20 event, the platform hosted a World Environment Day Global School Contest in which 7th graders at the International School of Ulaanbaatar (ISU) in Mongolia were declared the Global Winners for their awareness campaign on the environmental impact of plastic shopping bags, including research on plastic bag manufacturing processes, development of videos documenting plastic bag waste, and a school presentation at which reusable cloth shopping bags were sold to approximately 50 percent of the community.\n\nSarasota, Fla.'s Brookside Middle School won in the World Environment Day contest's North American sub-category for its mangrove propagule growth project while International School of Brussels in Belgium won the European sub-category, for their creation of a sustainable food source and composting program. The Middle-Eastern sub-category winner was [[Hridith Sudev]], a seventh grader from [[Indian School Salalah]] in Oman for his organization, '[[Project GreenWorld International]]' which helped promote sustainable awareness across the region through interactive projects. Hridith Sudev later went on to become an inventor and the organization has become a global environmental presence. The World Environment Day contest followed an Earth Day \"Green Schools\" contest regionally focused toward 6th to 12th grade students in the Western New York area.\n\nThe idea behind the platform was to encourage sustainability in students across the world. Despite the huge response, the platform was taken down two years later due to technical and economic constraints but has since remained as a positive legacy through the activities of students who were first recognized by the network.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Earth Summit]]\n** [[Agenda 21]]\n** [[Rio Declaration on Environment and Development]]\n* [[Durban III]] The conference opened on 22 September 2011\n* [[Planetary boundaries#United Nations endorsement|Planetary boundaries]]\n* [[Sustainable Development Goals]]\n* [[The United Nations Ocean Conference]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110420002837/http://www.uncsd2012.org/ United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development]\n* [[Brundtland Report|Our Common Future: Report of the World Commission on Environment and Development]]\n** [http://rio20.ebc.com.br/memoria/ Videos, photos and information about the Summit in Brazil]\n** [http://rio20.net/en/ Rio+20 Portal. Building the Peoples Summit]\n* [http://www.environmentmagazine.org/Archives/Back%20Issues/2012/March-April%202012/Rio_abstract.html Rio + 20: An Endangered Species?], March/April 2012 journal Environment\n* [http://www.adb.org/features/12-things-know-2012-sustainable-development Rio+20 and Sustainable Development: 12 Things to Know] Asian Development Bank\n* [https://www.un.org/en/sustainablefuture/ The Future We Want]\n* [http://www.earthsummit2012.org Earth Summit 2012]\n* [https://ecsdev.org/images/conference/5th-ICSD-2017-Program.pdf International Conference on Sustainable Development]\n* [http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415540254/ Only One Earth \u2013 the Long Road via Rio to Sustainable Development], the history from Stockholm to Rio by [[Felix Dodds]], Michael Strauss with [[Maurice Strong]]\n\n{{Sustainability}}\n